 {"id":"frankenpandas-pxv5","title":"fp-types: Scalar::semantic_eq rejects cross-kind Null comparison (73 fp-conformance fixtures affected)","description":"Observed: 73 of 108 fp-conformance bootstrap-suite fixture failures share pattern 'actual=Null(NaN), expected=Null(Null)'. These are semantically-equivalent missing values flagged as mismatched because Scalar::semantic_eq falls through to PartialEq for same-variant pairs, and Null(NaN) != Null(Null) under derived PartialEq (different discriminants).

Root: crates/fp-types/src/lib.rs:95 fn semantic_eq. The Float64 <-> Null(NaN) cross-kind case is handled, but Null(Null) <-> Null(NaN) is not. When fp-frame normalizes Float64 column missing cells to Null(NaN) (dtype-specific missing marker) and the fixture oracle serializes Null(Null) (canonical missing), the semantic_eq comparison rejects them.

Fix: make semantic_eq treat any two Null variants as equal — missingness is semantically indistinguishable for oracle parity. Add (Scalar::Null(_), Scalar::Null(_)) => true before the PartialEq fallback. Preserves existing Float64<->NaN bridging.

Impact: should flip 70+ fixture cases from Fail to Pass, unblocking ci_gate_g6, packet_suite_is_green_for_bootstrap_cases, differential_all_packets_green, differential_suite_produces_structured_drift, and several other top-level aggregates that cascade on the bootstrap suite.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-22T07:36:51.312248712Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-22T07:41:38.007651051Z","closed_at":"2026-04-22T07:41:38.005816859Z","close_reason":"shipped da3a25c: semantic_eq now bridges all Null-kind pairs (Null/NaN/NaT) as semantically equal for oracle-parity checks. fp-conformance case-level: 1141/108 → 1212/37 (71 fixtures recovered in one change across abs/astype/diff/rank/round/skew/value_counts/dt_*/resample/rolling with_nulls variants). Public PartialEq unchanged. Clippy clean; fp-types 62/62 tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
